string.text: The English people are descended from a mixture of Germanic tribes who migrated to the British Isles during the 5th and 6th centuries, and the indigenous Celtic populations who already inhabited the region. The Kingdom of England was established in the 9th and 10th centuries, when several Anglo-Saxon kingdoms were united under a single ruler. Over the following centuries, the English people and their rulers faced a series of challenges, including Viking invasions, Norman conquest, and political and religious upheaval. Today, the kingdom continues to gradually consolidate its power and expand its influence and can be regarded as a major player in European politics and commerce.

Berbers, Amazigh or known by Europeans as Moors are the people indigenous to the Maghreb region of North Africa with each region of the Maghreb containing several fully independent tribes. The Berbers have spawned many dynasties already, and before the 11th century most of Northwest Africa had become a Berber-speaking Muslim majority. Their traditional social structure is tribal, with a leader appointed to command a tribe. What differs from their European contemporaries is that women are able to have the power to govern.

In the 12th century, the Principality of bulgaria was formed there by descendants of Vladimir the Great. At the turn of 13th century principalities of bulgaria and Volhynia were united by Roman the Great creating a kingdom after 1253.

The French are descendants of the ancient populations of Gauls; Germanic tribes that settled France from east of the Rhine after the fall of the Roman Empire such as the Franks, from whom the name 'France' is derived. With the decline of the Empire, this federation of Germanic peoples continued to filter across the Rhine River between the third and seventh centuries. Their kingdom of today originated as West Francia, the western half of the original Carolingian Empire. A branch of this dynasty continued to rule until 987, when Hugh Capet was elected king and founded the Capetian dynasty whose tenth and current monarch is Louis IX.

In the 12th century, the Principality of Halych was formed there by descendants of Vladimir the Great. At the turn of 13th century principalities of Halych and Volhynia were united by Roman the Great creating a kingdom after 1253.

Balts are the oldest European ethnolinguistic group.They speak the various baltic languages, belonging to the larger Balto-Slavic branch of the Indo-European languages. One of the baltic people, Lithuanians, established Lithuanian Kingdom in the 13th century and later formed the Grand Duchy of Lithuania. It remained independent and was one of the last areas to adopt Christianity, beginning in the 14th century. In 1385, the Grand Duchy formed a dynastic union with Poland through the Union of Krewo. Later, the Union of Lublin (1569) created the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth.

The mamluk was a manumitted slave, distinguished from the ghulam, or household slave. After thorough training in martial arts, court etiquette and Islamic sciences, these slaves were freed but expected to remain loyal to their master and serve his household. Mamluks formed part of the military apparatus in Syria and Egypt since at least the 9th century, rising to become governing dynasties in Egypt and Syria as the Tulunid and Ikhshidid dynasties. Mamluk regiments constituted the backbone of Egypt's military under Ayyubid rule in the late 12th and early 13th centuries.

Following the Arab conquest of the Sasanian Empire in the medieval times, the Arab caliphates established their rule over the region for the next several centuries, during which the long process of the Islamization of Persia took place. A series of Muslim Persian kingdoms were later established on the fringes of the declining Abbasid Caliphate, including that of the ninth-century Samanids, under the reign of whom the Persian language was used officially for the first time in two centuries.

The Polish are considered to be descendants of the ancient West Slavic Lechites and other tribes that inhabited the Polish territories during the late antiquity. In the 10th century, the Western Polans — an influential tribe in the Greater Poland region — united various Lechitic clans under what became the Piast dynasty, thus creating the first Polish state. Today, the principalities are going through a time of great change and upheaval, facing both internal conflicts and external threats. Despite being divided into a number of smaller principalities, they are united by a common Slavic culture, language and the emergence of a distinctive Polish identity.

Slavs are the largest European ethnolinguistic group. They speak the various Slavic languages, belonging to the larger Balto-Slavic branch of the Indo-European languages. Slavs are geographically distributed throughout northern Eurasia, mainly inhabiting Central, Eastern and Southeastern Europe. A large Slavic minority is also scattered across the Baltic states and Central Asia, while a substantial Slavic diaspora is found throughout the Americas, as a result of immigration.

Italians, heirs to some of the most famous ancient civilizations, native to the Italian peninsula and with a tumultous and vast history, they are considered to be the descendants of the birthplaces of European civilization. Italy has been the starting point of phenomena of international impact such as the Roman Republic, the Roman Empire and the Roman Catholic Church.

The Swedes are a North Germanic people native to the Nordic region, primarily their kingdom of Sweden. During the Viking Age, they expanded east-and-southwards, going to Finland, the Baltics, even reaching the Black Sea and as far as Constantinople. The Swedish Vikings are believed to be the founding fathers of Kievan Rus. Originally a pagan people, the 11th century saw Christianity become the dominant religion and by 1050 the kingdom of Sweden and its peoples were counted as Christian.

The Teutonic Order is a Catholic religious institution founded as a military society 1190 in Acre. The Order of Brothers of the German House of Saint Mary in Jerusalem was formed to aid Christians on their pilgrimages to the Holy Land and to establish hospitals. Its members have commonly been known as the Teutonic Knights.
